[{"id":"VR861084","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">Show all your work for each part of the question. The parts within the question may not have equal weight.</p><br/><div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 1 shows two views of a variable capacitor that consists of two semicircular, parallel plates of the same size. The diagram on the left is labeled “Oblique View.” The diagram on the right is labeled “Front View.” The Oblique View shows the two plates labeled “Fixed Plate” and “Rotatable Plate.” The fixed plate is unshaded, and the rotatable plate is shaded. The midpoint of the straight edge of each plate is attached perpendicularly to a horizontal axle. The fixed plate is attached to the axle such that its straight edge is horizontal, and its curved edge is below the axle. The rotatable plate is attached to the axle such that its straight edge moves upward and to the right. The lower part of the rotatable plate partially overlaps the left part of the fixed plate. The Front View shows that the overlapped portion of the two plates is about one third of each plate’s surface area. The angle formed by the straight edges of the two plates, and located above and to the right of the axle, measures theta.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR861084.g05.svg\"/></div>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">A variable capacitor consists of two semicircular, parallel plates of the same size, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>. One plate is fixed in place, while the other plate can be rotated through various angular positions, resulting in a varying amount of overlapping plate area. The capacitance is determined by the amount of overlapping area and the distance between the plates. Also indicated in the figure is the angle <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\"><math alttext=\"theta\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>θ</mi></math></span></span> between the straight edges of the plates.</p>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">The capacitor plates have been given equal-but-opposite amounts of charge, and a group of students wishes to experimentally determine the amount of charge on the plates. The students have an assortment of standard measurement equipment that includes a voltmeter probe, shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>. The voltmeter probe can measure the potential difference between two conducting surfaces by touching one of the measurement tips to each conductor. Assume that using the voltmeter does not significantly affect the charge distribution or the amount of charge on the plates. Also assume the net charge on each plate resides uniformly only on the areas where they overlap.</p>\n</div></div>\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 2 shows a voltmeter with two wires connected to it. The loose end of each wire has a voltmeter measurement tip, one of which is shaded, and the other is unshaded.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR861084.g06.svg\"/></div>\n</div></div><div class=\"item_part part_id:A part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"A\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Describe</span> a procedure for collecting data that would allow the students to determine the charge on one of the capacitor plates by making a linear graph. In your description, include the measurements to be made along with the corresponding equipment needed for each measurement. Provide enough detail so that the experiment could be replicated, including any steps necessary to reduce experimental uncertainty.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR861084_rubric"},{"id":"VR861084","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) For the data collected in the procedure from part (a), <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">describe</span> how the students could create a linear graph and how that graph could be analyzed to determine the charge on one plate of the capacitor.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR861084_rubric"},{"id":"VR861084","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:Ci part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Ci\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Another group of students wishes to experimentally determine a numerical value for <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"epsilon sub 0\"><math alttext=\"epsilon sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>ε</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span>, the electric permittivity of free space. This group has a parallel-plate capacitor in which the separation distance between the plates can be varied. The plates on this capacitor completely overlap one another and have an area <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A equals 0.160 square meter\"><math alttext=\"A equals 0.160 square meter\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0.160</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></span></span>. With the capacitor connected to a battery of potential difference <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta V equals 5.60 volts\"><math alttext=\"delta V equals 5.60 volts\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Δ</mtext><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5.60</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mtext>V</mtext></math></span></span>, the students are able to determine the charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>Q</mi></math></span></span> on the capacitor’s plates for various plate separation distances <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>d</mi></math></span></span>. The table shows the results of the experiment.</p><div class=\"table_wrapper\"><table class=\"tgroup cols:4\"><col class=\"colspec align:center colname:col1 colnum:1 colwidth:60\"/><col class=\"colspec align:center colname:col2 colnum:2 colwidth:60\"/><col class=\"colspec align:center colname:col3 colnum:3 colwidth:60\"/><col class=\"colspec colname:col4 colnum:4 colwidth:60\"/><tbody class=\"tbody\"><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d, in millimeters\"><math alttext=\"d, in millimeters\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>d</mi><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mpadded><mo>(</mo><mpadded><mi>mm</mi></mpadded><mo>)</mo></mpadded></math></span></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q, in nanocoulombs\"><math alttext=\"Q, in nanocoulombs\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>Q</mi><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mpadded><mo>(</mo><mpadded><mi>nC</mi></mpadded><mo>)</mo></mpadded></math></span></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\"></td><td class=\"entry colname:col4\"></td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2.0\"><math alttext=\"2.0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2.0</mn></math></span></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"4.13\"><math alttext=\"4.13\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>4.13</mn></math></span></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\"></td><td class=\"entry colname:col4\"></td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2.5\"><math alttext=\"2.5\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2.5</mn></math></span></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3.54\"><math alttext=\"3.54\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3.54</mn></math></span></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\"></td><td class=\"entry colname:col4\"></td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"4.0\"><math alttext=\"4.0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>4.0</mn></math></span></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2.00\"><math alttext=\"2.00\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2.00</mn></math></span></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\"></td><td class=\"entry colname:col4\"></td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"7.0\"><math alttext=\"7.0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>7.0</mn></math></span></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1.14\"><math alttext=\"1.14\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1.14</mn></math></span></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\"></td><td class=\"entry colname:col4\"></td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"9.5\"><math alttext=\"9.5\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>9.5</mn></math></span></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0.93\"><math alttext=\"0.93\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>0.93</mn></math></span></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\"></td><td class=\"entry colname:col4\"></td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\" colspan=\"4\">Notes: <span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span>Plate area <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A equals 0.160 square meter\"><math alttext=\"A equals 0.160 square meter\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0.160</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></span></span>,<span class=\"formatted_line_break delivery_mode:Both\"></span>Capacitor potential difference <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta V equals 5.60 volts\"><math alttext=\"delta V equals 5.60 volts\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5.60</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></span></span></td></tr></tbody></table></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c)</p><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">i. Indicate what quantities could be graphed to yield a straight line that could be used to calculate an experimental value for <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"epsilon sub 0\"><math alttext=\"epsilon sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>ε</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span>.</p><p class=\"list_paragraph\"></p><p class=\"list_paragraph\">Horizontal axis: __________          Vertical axis: __________</p></li></ul><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Use the remaining columns in the table, as needed, to <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">record</span> any quantities indicated that are not already provided in the table. Label each column and include units.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR861084_rubric"},{"id":"VR861084","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:Cii part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Cii\"><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">ii. On the grid in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span>, <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">plot</span> the data points for the quantities indicated in part (c)(i). Clearly <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">scale and label</span> all axes, including units. On the same grid, <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">draw</span> a straight line that best represents the data.</p></li></ul><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 3 shows a 25 by 25 grid.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR861084.g08.svg\"/></div></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR861084_rubric"},{"id":"VR861084","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:D part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"D\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) Using the line drawn in part (c)(ii), <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">calculate</span> an experimental value for <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"epsilon sub 0\"><math alttext=\"epsilon sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>ε</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span>.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR861084_rubric"}]